answers.body_markdown:
The `exports` object is exactly equivalent to what a `require` from another file resolves to. So, when you assign to a `ProxyUrl` property of the object, the imported object will have a property with a `ProxyUrl` property.

If you want the export to be *just* the function, rather than an object with a property, then assign to the `module.exports`:

```
const proxy = {
    host: &#39;127.0.0.1&#39;
};

module.exports = () =&gt; {
    return `http://${proxy.host}`;
};
```

and then you can

```
const proxyUrl = require(&#39;./proxy.js&#39;);
console.log(proxyUrl());
```

Otherwise, with your original code, you&#39;d have to access the `ProxyUrl` property of the `require`d object first:

```
const { ProxyUrl } = require(&#39;./proxy.js&#39;);
console.log(ProxyUrl());
```

